Ask HN: Windows Dev Kit 2023: Impressions 5 months in?
text:
Hello!

Back when Project Volterra launched, I was very tempted to get one of these devices but the stock ran out quickly. I see that the device is back in stock now so, once again, I'm tempted to buy one :)

For context: In my case, I would be using the device as my primary desktop. My workflow is mostly to SSH into a powerful machine I have in the garage via a terminal and VSCode, so the device on my desk doesn't matter that much really. I occasionally use Lightroom and the Office apps, and have a couple of ancient games in Steam. I specifically do not target Windows nor arm64 in my development (yet?), but having what seems to be a snappy and power-efficient little device on my desk for a good price sounds neat. Yeah, getting one of these would mostly be a cool-factor kind of purchase...

For extra context, this would be replacing a Mac Pro 2013 (the 6-core trashcan) that I have running Windows 11 natively. I've been trying to research what the performance differences would be but it's really hard to compare such an old device with this newer arm64-based machine. Oh, and it would be hooked to a 4K monitor via DP, but that seems to be fine as far as I can tell.

The question to you is: if you have been using one of these devices for the past few months, what are your impressions overall now that the hype has cooled off?

And... any new developments on running Linux on this thing? The internet seems kinda quiet about this topic... but given that both FreeBSD and OpenBSD seem to run on it, it's hard to believe that Linux doesn't at all yet.

Thanks!

Show HN: Icsp â€“ Command-line iCalendar (.ics) to CSV utility
text:
Hey folks, I've written this pure bash ICS to CSV conversion tool after needing it for a personal use case.

It all started with realizing that the Google Calendar REST api was too much of a hassle to integrate for a one-off use case (need to change account settings, do a Oauth login & manage tokens...). I then remembered that calendar exports were just a few clicks away in the .ics format, so I decided to use that instead.

I couldn't find anything online other than half broken scripts or language-specific libraries to parse .ics files, so I then went ahead and wrote a straight forward, pure bash implementation for CLI usage.

Hope this is useful for others as well!

I put in a few examples to try out in the readme on Github, let me know if you try it out!

title: Ask HN: Why don't banks have API tokens like GitHub?
text: I haven't seen this anywhere so I figured it's worth asking. I'd really like to have a read only token that could be issued by my bank so I can have a little web client pull the balance data and update a budget for me. Yes I know there's mint budgeting and all that. I'm skeptical of handing the keys over to others and I'd like to DIY this. Is there some regulatory reason this doesn't exist? Are there any banks that have API access that clients can't use? Every time I switch banks to something that has cash envelope accounting they take it away or merge with another bank and I have to start the whole process over again. I'm beginning to think it would be easier to just do it myself if I had API access.
